		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				In my opinion, you have to decide how far you want to go with roleplaying.  If you roleplay to the extent that you can not interact with other races and classes then you need to either find yourself a good group of similar PC's that play regularly enough to make it worth your while, or you need to decide when a lower amount of RP'ing is more beneficial. <br>  <br> I go through phases myself where I will either play the way you described, or I will simply stay in character showing deep contempt for those who my race/class would not associate with.   <br>  <br> Being a paladin makes this even tougher, if I run past a DE Shadowknight who calls for help, do I help?  Is he more evil than the monster attacking him?  In these cases, I aid that person but I do not buff or heal them, exchange pleasantries, etc.   <br>  <br> If I'm speaking in my native language, people do the &quot;use common dude&quot; routine.  Ignoring that doesn't help, they just say it over and over.  In that case I use emotes, such as /em scoffs at your race's ignorance to other languages.  Or something like that.  I don't, however, speak in my language while grouped, I had an occasion where we were learning from each other and one person kept forgetting to switch back.  In heated battle scenarios that's not always a good thing. <br>  <br> I'd suggest that you have to decide what is more appropriate for the situation and how much alienation will make the game no longer enjoyable or interactive.
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
						<div class="SignatureText">
						Gundrun Naranek <br> Spoiled Rotten Paladin <br> 
						</div>
							

